messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

I inspected the blueprint registrations and the routes in app/api/cms/admin.py.

- The cms blueprint is registered in app/__init__.py with url_prefix "/cms".
- The admin_api blueprint is registered inside that cms blueprint with url_prefix "/admin".
- Each @admin_api.route(...) defines the remaining path and (optionally) an explicit methods=[...] list.

Below are all endpoints found in app/api/cms/admin.py with their full HTTP request paths (path parameters wrapped in {}) and which HTTP methods are acceptable.

Notes about interpretation:
- If a route decorator does not specify methods, Flask’s route defaults to handling GET (and Flask also provides HEAD and OPTIONS automatically for GET routes). I treat such routes as accepting GET, HEAD and OPTIONS.
- If methods is explicitly provided (e.g. methods=["PUT"]), that HTTP method is accepted; Flask also provides an automatic OPTIONS response for routes with explicit methods, so I mark OPTIONS accepted for those as well. HEAD is only accepted automatically for routes that allow GET.
- No route in this file accepts all methods, and no route explicitly lists TRACE or PATCH.

Endpoints

1) Path: /cms/admin/permission
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: true
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

2) Path: /cms/admin/users
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: true
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

3) Path: /cms/admin/user/{uid}/password
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

4) Path: /cms/admin/user/{uid}
- (DELETE route)
  - all_methods: false
  - HEAD: false
  - POST: false
  - OPTIONS: true
  - TRACE: false
  - GET: false
  - PUT: false
  - DELETE: true
  - PATCH: false
- (PUT route)
  - all_methods: false
  - HEAD: false
  - POST: false
  - OPTIONS: true
  - TRACE: false
  - GET: false
  - PUT: true
  - DELETE: false
  - PATCH: false
Note: /cms/admin/user/{uid} has two separate handlers registered — one for DELETE and one for PUT.

5) Path: /cms/admin/group/all
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: true
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

6) Path: /cms/admin/group/{gid}
- GET route:
  - all_methods: false
  - HEAD: true
  - POST: false
  - OPTIONS: true
  - TRACE: false
  - GET: true
  - PUT: false
  - DELETE: false
  - PATCH: false
- PUT route:
  - all_methods: false
  - HEAD: false
  - POST: false
  - OPTIONS: true
  - TRACE: false
  - GET: false
  - PUT: true
  - DELETE: false
  - PATCH: false
- DELETE route:
  - all_methods: false
  - HEAD: false
  - POST: false
  - OPTIONS: true
  - TRACE: false
  - GET: false
  - PUT: false
  - DELETE: true
  - PATCH: false

7) Path: /cms/admin/group
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

8) Path: /cms/admin/permission/dispatch/batch
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

9) Path: /cms/admin/permission/remove
- all_methods: false
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation summary
- Full path for each endpoint is the concatenation of the app-level /cms prefix and the admin blueprint’s /admin prefix plus the @admin_api.route path, e.g. /cms + /admin + /permission => /cms/admin/permission.
- Where methods are not explicitly given in the decorator, the route is declared (in code) without methods and therefore is a GET route; I marked HEAD and OPTIONS accepted because Flask provides them for GET routes.
- Where methods are explicitly given (e.g. ["PUT"], ["POST"], ["DELETE"]), only those methods are accepted in code; OPTIONS is also provided automatically by Flask for routes that declare methods, so OPTIONS is marked true for those routes. HEAD is only true for routes that allow GET.
- No route explicitly accepts TRACE, PATCH, or an “all methods” wildcard.
